  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Reducing the Health Impacts of E-Waste Recycling in Accra, Ghana</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The informal settlement of Agbogloshie in Ghana is one of the biggest dumping grounds in the world for discarded computer hardware and other electronic waste. Redundant equipment from developed nations pours into Ghana on a daily basis, and among the growing mountains of e-waste, people scavenge to salvage scrap metal in return for as little as a dollar or two a day. The process is messy and dangerous with the rubber and plastic coatings of wires and circuit boards melted on open fires in order to reclaim copper and other valuable metals. Plumes of black smoke rise above the slum and its open-air food market, exposing not only scrap workers but also the whole community to hazardous levels of lead, dioxins and other poisons. Workers report difficulty breathing, and problems related to the skin and stomach are widespread. Blacksmith Initiative UK is working with international environmental health experts and a committed local campaign group, to carry out consultations with local communities to find solutions that can help to improve the health and livelihoods of local communities and the environment.</narrative>
  </description>
